,Not Recommended,427810,21017970,"Posted: 6 February, 2016",all,Your Gay Father,"I enjoyed Calendula for the forty minutes it lasted. Or rather, I thought I was enjoying where it was going. Every time you complete a puzzle you get a small walking section (where you can only go straight, and the game turns you through glitches if necessary) followed by a brief fmv clip. I'm going to spoil the ""twist"" in this review, but honestly, its Shyamalan levels of dumb.At the beginning of each level you are booted back to the main menu screen. That much you probably already know. The majority of gameplay takes place here. This is where the game is at its best. It's extremely fun to solve abstract puzzles that ♥♥♥♥ with your perception of the menus, the space around them, and the ambient audio. It's all very interesting, and I absolutely love it during this, even if it is a tad too easy.Once you solve the puzzle, you get a walking segment. The environments differ each time, but they're always fairly basic corridors. After the walking is where it gets juicy. At some point during the walk glitches will appear and the game will fade into an unsettling fmv clip that implies more is going on.The game has a ton of eye imagery, some are photorealistic during the transition to fmv. One puzzle has you go into an ingame fake chat room where somebody screams at you to ""please stop"" and asks why you're doing ""this"", then repeating ""WHY"" repeatedly before he 'logs off'. At one point during a walking section you approach a globe, and it darkens as you approach, almost seeming to mold. The game seems to be about some large world government, cult, or Umbrella-style science gone wrong sort of story. It gets you hooked the moment you start considering the first few fmvs and only stacks evidence from there.What's the ending, I hear you ask? None of the above. You're a kid named Calendula being born. The ending is atrocious.I was honestly tempted to refund this game, but seeing as how I absolutely adored the puzzle section, I've decided to leave my money with Blooming Buds. I loved your game, but don't lead me on with a story. Next time you guys make a game, include a narrative that isn't a bunch of disconnected parts that can't be related to each other, okay? The ending is what REALLY brought this down."
