,Not Recommended,427810,29704883,Posted: 4 February,all,ScouSin,"Minor spoilers below, so heads up.Calendula is a horror game in a rising subgenre of ""haunted games"".  This type of game looks like it originated from the all too common haunted game creepypasta stories online.  I've played some games that do it well, but unfortunately I feel like Calendula is half-hearted on the haunted aspect, and has too little gameplay to be fulfilling.In terms of gameplay, most of the time you'll be navigating the game's options or interface to get a password which you need to load the game's save (actually basically ""go here to progress the game"").  The game itself asking for and accepting an arbitrary password doesn't feel very haunted.  If you were somehow progressing by adjusting the game's settings, as opposed to getting a password to input elsewhere, that would feel more how I expect a ""game that doesn't want to be played"" to act.For the horror aspects, there is some imagery that suggests there is something sinister going on, which is cool.  It also tries to create a haunting atmosphere by being vague and haunting.  I appreciate the value of not revealing the monster, so to speak, but this game did too little to suggest there was any danger, or even anything to fear.  At the very beginning there is a sequence where you play in a first person section walking down a hall slowly.  I've seen this in horror games before, I was worried about looking behind myself, but then I saw I couldn't.  I was basically on rails.  It took two more of these before I decided there were no actual scares in the game (jump scares or otherwise).  Having a haunting atmosphere is pointless if there is no chance for a pay off.  It's fine if nothing comes out at me and scares me, but I knew without a doubt halfway through that it would never happen, ever.  So I wasn't worried about anything anymore.The TL;DR version: Calendula is short, not scary, and the gameplay feels half-completed."
,Not Recommended,427810,28926451,Posted: 1 January,all,Blackfang321,"While I appreciate these types of games, this one really wouldn't be worth more than $1.  It takes less than an hour to beat and, to me, didn't truely offer any better meta experience than other games could (such as Stanley Parable).  The imagery felt cliche and although the ""ending"" may or may not come as a surprise to some people, to me it was fairly obvious half way through.This would have made a decent freebie browser based experience, but for me it came and went quickly, left no lasting impressions, and just wasn't worth the already discounted price.I would have loved to see them take the concepts in this game and incorporate them into something larger and more subtle."
