,Recommended,427810,20921262,"Posted: 2 February, 2016",all,luukiead,"I would suggest taking this game with a little pinch of salt. The game is less 'meta' and more just plain glitchy. It's fun, and the puzzles are a great mixture between challenging, do-able, and unnerving, and the music in particular was very good, as were some of the visual elements (although not all of it- it runs on Unity, after all). But it is not horror. It's definitely creepy in parts, and if you have an aversion to glitching or technology with slight self-awareness then this may get you feeling a little panicked. What ruins it, however, is the storyline element, which is a little contrived, the allegory a little forced, and the ending less of a big spooky bang and more of a tired mumbling of ""Oh, no. Not this again!""Play it, definitely. It's a nice little indie game with a lot of atmosphere, which for the most part makes up for any downfalls."
,Recommended,427810,20924855,"Posted: 2 February, 2016",all,Audio Fatigue,"Calendula is a surreal experience and sort-of puzzle game. It will appeal to you if you're the kind of person that dives straight into the options menu when you first launch a game.Clendula pits you in a fight with the game itself in an effort to actually ""play"" it. It will mess with you every way a game can in order to not be played. You're going to have to use your accumulated knowledge of in-game menus to win this one.That said, I enjoyed this game quite a bit. In terms of music and tone, Calendula nails it. The only thing I can complain about is the short length. I beat it in about 45 minutes, but I completed it feeling satisfied."
